ic artist and inventor, and other polymaths such as philosopher Giulio "Delminio" Camillo (1480-1544), physician and naturalist Francisco Hernández de Toledo (1514-1587), and writer Miguel de Cervantes (1547-1616). This concern with futurity is inspired by the Renaissance itself, a period defined by visions of the future, as well as by recent theorizing of temporality in Renaissance and Queer Studies. This transdisciplinary volume is at the cutting edge of the humanities, medical humanities, scientific discovery, and avant-garde artistic expression.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aArt and sciencexForecasting. 0aArt and sciencezEuropey15th century. 0aArt and sciencezEuropey16th century. 0aArts in general. 0aHistory (General). 7aART / History / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aartist.  aartistic rebirth.  aavant garde artistic expression.  adelminio.  aeuropean imperialism.  afrancisco hernandez de toledo.  afuturity.  agiulio camillo.  aglobal early modern world.  ahumanities.  aintersections.  ainventor.  aleonardo da vinci.  amedical humanities.  amiguel de cervantes.  anaturalist.  anew science.  aphilosopher.  aphysician.  apolymaths.  aqueer studies.  arenaissance.  ascientific discovery.1 aArmas, Frederick A. de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlack, Charlene Villaseñor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlack, Charlene Villaseñor, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEamon, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFarago, Claire, econtributor.4ctb